text: Diano, great to have you with us on BT Sport. Let's talk about the movie.
It's being billed as Ronaldo the man, Ronaldo the person.
What impression do you think people will have of you once they watch the film?
To be honest, I'm not worried about the impression going to have about me
because it's such a natural movie that I was not thinking about that.
Of course, we're always thinking to give a good image.
But when you will see the movie, you will see that it's so natural
because I'm not an actor. I don't know how to act.
So I think the end of the day, I think the result was great.
We see a lot of your early life and we hear a lot about that.
How difficult was it to cope with being away from home at such a young age,
but still remain focused on your football?
I'm always saying it was the toughest time in my life.
It was when I left my family with eleven years old to live in a different world,
which is his Lisbon. In the same country, but it looked like it's a different part of the world.
I was cry almost every day to miss my family, but I'm not regretted
because it was probably the more intense moments in my life that I lived through.
So without sacrifice, we cannot win nothing.
So I did a unbelievable sacrifice, my family too.
And I think I did a good option.
When you had those tough times, could you ever have imagined being in the place that you are today?
Of course not. Of course not.
But I always thinking when I take that decision, I will be a professional player.
I will be something in a football.
This is I feel, because I was feeling from the beginning that I was different than other ones.
I was more special. I was a special kid.
If you can speak with my coaches, my friends, my teammates,
everyone see that I was special.
At that time, even with 15 years old, 16 years old,
at that time, he was at the moment, everybody knows that he is the best player in the world,
the best ever. But at that time, with his age, he was the best player in the world,
the best ever, because with that age, nobody could do what he was doing.
Was something unbelievable.
Something that really comes across in the movie is a very nice sight to you.
Actually, we see you with a very strong bond with your son.
How has father had changed you?
Well, change everything.
To have Cristiano in a family,
a one-member in a family, a person who has your blood, it's unbelievable.
It's a great feeling, because I always dream to have a kid,
young, I had with 25,
and to have Cristiano to follow his father to see his father in TV,
in life, to play football, and when he'd be like me for me, it's kind of a dream.
Are you surprised by some of the top-level sports journalists still working in this industry
who write about you? Yet, they still have some negative perceptions of you,
because they still don't really know you.
It's part of the business.
I have to respect that.
They have to sell.
They have to make money.
It's normal. It's part of the business.
I respect that.
But these people, they are not my friends.
So it's normal.
Maybe in the beginning I was worried people would speak bad.
But now, this is not interferent.
The way I see the football, my life,
personal life or a professional life for me, this doesn't matter anymore.
In England, there's often a sense that players are given a hard time by journalists,
but also by pundits.
So often fellow professionals, do you think they have the right to criticize you
and be critical of your performances?
Of course. I think it's...
What I respect more, the people, is they criticize me about my job.
This is our respect.
And the people should do that because there is jobs
to do with the analysis of what they see.
I'm used to be criticized many years.
And I know to leave it at for me is not a problem anymore.
I live with that comfortable.
Looking over your career, what would you say was your greatest performance?
A greatest performance.
It's tough.
It's tough. I prefer to say a year.
Probably the last two years, last year, when we win the Champions League here in Madrid.
But I have so many great moments.
Thanks God, not just here, but in Manchester too, when we win the Champions League, the cops,
the league, when I win the Golden Ball, Golden Boot, here in Real Madrid.
I did the same and I win the same.
It's hard to say a specific moment.
I had so great moments in my career so far that it's not will be fair to mention only one.
I have to mention many years.
The last eight years in my point of view, it was amazing.
And to be in the top level, eight years is not easy. It's not for everyone.
It's hard.
Okay, so what's been the most disappointing moment of your career?
Disappointing.
It's kind of the same. When we lost the finals, Champions League or cops.
When you lost the big competitions when you don't go through
and the groups, national team or Real Madrid or whatever,
it's the most complicated moment. It's when you lost.
When you lost and when you lost the finals or it's the most hardest moments.
But it's part of the job.
And we have to live with that because it's normal.
You've played under some amazing football managers as well.
What have you learnt from each of them?
I learnt everything with...
I learnt many things with everyone.
Not only one, but with everyone.
I think it's good.
This makes me feel happy because all the coaches that I had, I learnt something.
Some great. I'm a happy person.
I'm a lucky person.
To share my football the way I am.
The trainings with these great coaches that I had in the past and now.
Someone who's having a bit of a hard time right now is Joseph Merino.
Where on the scale of top football managers would you rate him?
I will put him in the top. I'm always saying that.
It's a good coach.
He did many good things.
He win many trophies for the other clubs.
I don't want to speak about the other coaches because my coach is now in its vanitais.
And I'm comfortable for sure.
We're going to win many things together.
I'm happy with that.
What would you say are the main differences between the Premier League and La Liga?
For me, in my opinion, it's the best leagues in the world.
Spain is in English.
I think in England there are more honest players.
They are faster and stronger than here.
But here they have other points. They are more technical.
It's different.
But I think both.
It's great.
I had the opportunity to play in both.
I'm so happy because I think they are great.
If you see the Champions League, they always.
Spanish team and English teams in semifinals.
That it's mean that the football is great.
Who do you think are the most exciting young players that are coming through?
You see many players with the potential.
For example, I will mention the other players.
Of Madrid, of 16, still young.
But we can see that it's a good player.
As are, for example, the number 7 of Manchester Depay.
It's a good player too.
Pogda, maybe.
Neymar.
I think you have many, many good players.
It's good for the football.
We see you in the movie when Lionel Messi wins his fourth ball.
It's evident to see your disappointment in your face.
Do you think having that rivalry between you has been good for both you and for him?
I'm always disappointing when I'm lost.
It's normal.
I'm always going to be like that.
I'm not a fake person.
I'm going to hide when I feel disappointing.
But it's not the pin of me.
For example, in the ball, Don De Penelope made the pins of votes.
And votes, you never know what's going to happen.
For example, Golden Boot, Don De Penelope made the pins of statistics.
It's completely different.
I'm not complaining because I win three times.
I'm never thinking that I will win one goal in the ball.
So two in three for me, it's great.
It gives me great motivation to still work good and hard to achieve more if it's possible.
I'm not worried about that because I think the things are coming naturally in the right moment.
I want more and more.
I still have many years to play football and I want to win more things.
Do you think having that intense rivalry makes you a better player?
Having someone who was constantly compared to you, does that make you more motivated to be even better?
But I'm almost motivated. I don't need other players to motivate myself.
But of course, Messi is an unbelievable player.
And maybe in the end of me, he pushed me harder to be better and better.
Probably, yes.
You don't need to compare Cristiano with this player or any other player.
Cristiano is motivation. He has always...
...all the motivation. He was six years in the United.
He was improving a lot.
And nobody did like him. He was the best ever in the United.
He is the best ever in Real Madrid.
And keeping that performance, it's very difficult.
Just a player like Cristiano, just Cristiano can do it.
I try to be the best professional in my job.
I try to be the best all the time.
Sometimes it's not possible because you know, we are human beings and we are not machines.
But in my mind, I'm the best and I work like the best.
So this is going to be my...
...the way I see my life to the end of my life.
So this is what I want and what I want to be.
